author: Staff Reports sports@s-t.com
title: UMD Roundup: Corsairs cruise in 9-0 tennis win over Southern Maine
text: Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 8:24 PM By Staff Reports Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 8:24 PM Â» Social News Lakeville's Jenna Lahaie notched a 6-0, 6-1 win at first singles to help lead the UMass Dartmouth women's tennis team to a 9-0 Little East Conference win over the University of Southern Maine on Saturday in Gorham. Kerry Magoon (6-2, 6-2 at number two), Mattapoisett's Maggie LeBrun (6-1, 6-3 at number three) and Dartmouth's Kirsten Rose (8-0 pro-set win at number four) added victories for UMD. Mollie McCaffrey (6-1, 6-4 at number five) and Samantha Rollings (6-0, 6-0 at number six) were also victorious. Lahaie and LeBrun teamed up for an 8-3 win at first doubles. Magoon and Kheyla Orival were 8-3 winners at second doubles and the team of Rose and McCaffrey combined for an 8-0 win at third doubles. UMD (6-5, 4-3 LEC) plays Lesley College at Buckingham, Browne & Nichols in Cambridge on Tuesday. Southern Maine dropped to 2-9 overall and 0-7 in the conference. WOMEN'S SOCCER UMD 1, Southern Maine 0, OT Talia D'Ambruoso scored 9:45 into overtime to give the Corsairs a Little East Conference win over the Huskies in Gorham. Madison Boucher made one save for UMD (5-4-1, 2-1-1 LEC) and Marissa Temple turned away seven shots for Southern Maine ( 3-8-0, 0-4-0 LEC). The Corsairs play a 4 p.m. game at Roger Williams University on Wednesday. MEN'S SOCCER UMD 4, Southern Maine 0 Akere Tambi scored a pair of goals to help lead the Corsairs to a Little East Conference win over the Huskies at Cressy Field in Dartmouth. Stephan Teixeira and Wilfred Ghanyea also scored for the Corsairs, who led 1-0 at halftime. Andre Reis made two saves in net for UMD (6-4-1, 1-1-2 LEC), which plays a 7 p.m. non-conference game at Roger Williams University on Tuesday. WOMEN'S VOLLEYBALL Framingham State 3, UMD 0 St. Joseph's 3, UMD 0 Christina Spinazola had seven assists for the Corsairs in a 25-15, 25-18, 25-14 loss to the Rams in a match played at St. Joseph's of Maine in Standish. Megan Ronaghan had six kills and Eliza Bowes notched five kills in a 25-14, 25-17, 25-21 loss to the home team. Carina Filosa, Westport's Kayla Kirby and New Bedford's Jasmine Burriss all had eight digs. UMD (9-13, 1-2 Little East Conference) plays a 6 p.m. conference match at Rhode Island College on Tuesday. CROSS COUNTRY James Early Invitational Jason Karakaedos covered an 8K course in 27:03.64 to finish 20th and help lead the Corsairs to a 10th-place finish in a field of 38 teams in a meet run at Stanley Park in Westfield. Sean Herlihy crossed the line 22nd in 27:06.14. Reme DiGiovanni finished 28th on a 3.1-mile (5K) course in 19:45.70 to help lead the women's team to a 13th-place finish in a field of 39 teams at the same venue. Kirstie Harnden ended up 48th in 20:10.46. The Corsairs will compete in the Connecticut College Invitational on Saturday. FIELD HOCKEY UMD 2, Westfield State 1 (OT) Despite dominating the game, it took until overtime for the UMass Dartmouth field hockey team to get past Westfield State. Jill Levrault scored both goals unassisted, he second coming in the 76th minute. The Corsairs had a 24-5 edge in shots and a 17-0 lead in penalty corners. Goalie Allison Burke made on save. UMD (10-3, 6-1 LEC) hosts Plymouth State at 1 p.m. on Saturday. By Staff Reports
